, Depression-era relief gardens, victory gardens, and community gardens—each representing a consistent impulse to return to gardening during times of social and economic change. In this critical history of community gardening in America, the most comprehensive review of the greening of urban communities to date, Laura J. Lawson documents the evolution of urban garden programs in the United States. Her vibrant narrative focuses on the values associated with gardening, the ebb and flow of campaigns during times of social and economic crisis, organizational strategies of these primarily volunteer campaigns, and the sustainability of current programs.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunity gardensxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aJardins communautairesxHistoirex20e sièclexÉtats-UnisxUnited StatesxUSA. 4aGardening. 4aGeneral. 7aGARDENING / General.2bisacsh1 aLawson, Laura, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024343940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093155840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520931558423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520931558/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles